Shortly before that, student unrest took place, which led to the temporary closure of St. Professor Golovnin sent many young people abroad, and N. I. Pirogov entrusted their leadership. Experienced persons were sent abroad to familiarize themselves with university procedures, including K. D. Kavelin; in Russia itself, all persons who could be considered knowledgeable in this matter were interviewed, and the draft of the new charter in translation was discussed by the best European authorities. Few of the legislative monuments had such a detailed and comprehensive preliminary development as the university charter of 1863, which introduced docent, university self-government, university student court, multiplied the number of departments, increased the remuneration of professors.